   "source": [
    "Infinite Iterators - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "76c50f02-85f0-4829-baa4-9b25ecad9b6d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "itertools.count\n",
    "\n",
    "Lazy iterator\n",
    "The count function is an infinite iterator\n",
    "similar to range -> start, step\n",
    "different from range -> no stop, infinit, start and step cam be any numeric type (float, complex, Decimal, bool)\n",
    "\n",
    "Example\n",
    "\n",
    "count(10, 2) -> 10, 12, 14, ...\n",
    "count(10.5, 0.1) -> 10.5, 10.6, 10.7, ...\n",
    "\n",
    "takewhile(lambda x: x < 10.8, count(10.5, 0.1)) -> 10.5, 10.6, 10.7"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "e5facbbe-57a8-42ee-b8e2-1883d9e718e4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "itertools.cycle\n",
    "\n",
    "Lazy iterator\n",
    "The cycle function allows us to loop over a finite iterable indefinitely\n",
    "\n",
    "Example\n",
    "\n",
    "cycle(['a', 'b', 'c']) -> 'a', 'b', 'c', 'a', 'b', ...\n",
    "\n",
    "Important\n",
    "If the argument of cycle is itself an iterator -> iterators become exhausted\n",
    "Cycle will still produce an infinite sequence\n",
    "-> does not stop after the iterator becomes exhausted"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "d84fd8db-40fb-4870-b9cd-4edbb83df98f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "itertools.repeat\n",
    "\n",
    "Lazy iterator\n",
    "The repeat function simply yields the same value indefinitely\n",
    "\n",
    "repeat('spam') -> 'spam', 'spam', 'spam', ...\n",
    "\n",
    "Optionally you can specify a count to make the iterator finite\n",
    "\n",
    "repeat('spam', 3) -> 'spam', 'spam', 'spam'\n",
    "\n",
    "Caveat:\n",
    "The items yielded by repeat are the same object\n",
    "-> they each reference the same object in memory"
   ]
  },
